            <h1>Why i Switched from VS Code to Neovim</h1>
            <p class="blog-meta">Feb 21, 2026 · 5 min read</p>
          </header>

          <section class="blog-content">
            <p>
              i used VS Code for three years. it was comfortable, had great
              extensions, and just worked. So why did i switch to Neovim? The
              honest answer is — speed and control.
            </p>

            <h2>The Problem with VS Code</h2>
            <p>
              VS Code is a great editor but it's an Electron app, which means
              it's essentially a browser running your editor. On older machines
              or large projects, this shows. Startup time, memory usage, and
              occasional sluggishness were things i just accepted — until i
              didn't.
            </p>

            <h2>My First Week with Neovim</h2>
            <p>
              Brutal. i won't sugarcoat it. i spent more time configuring than
              coding. But something clicked around day five — i stopped reaching
              for the mouse. My hands stayed on the keyboard and i started
              moving through code faster than i ever had before.
            </p>

            <h2>What i Use Now</h2>
            <p>
              i run LazyVim as my base config. it gives me LSP support, fuzzy
              finding, and git integration out of the box. From there i've added
              a few plugins for my specific workflow.
            </p>

            <h2>Should You Switch?</h2>
            <p>
              Probably not if you're just starting out. VS Code is genuinely
              excellent and the learning curve of Neovim is real. But if you've
              been coding for a while and want more control over your
              environment, it's worth trying for a week.
            </p>
          </section>

